        if str1[i-1] == str2[j-1]:
            lcs[index-1] = str1[i-1]
            i -= 1
            j -= 1
            index -= 1
        elif dp[i-1][j] > dp[i][j-1]:
            i -= 1
        else:
            j -= 1
    return "".join(lcs)
```
Explanation: The above code implements the dynamic programming approach to find the longest common subsequence of two input strings. The algorithm works by creating a 2D array `dp` of size `(m+1) x (n+1)`, where `m` and `n` are the lengths of the two input strings. The elements of the array are initialized to 0. The algorithm then iterates through the elements of the array, comparing the characters at each position in the two input strings. If the characters match, the value at the current position in the array is incremented by 1. If the characters do not match, the maximum value between the values at the previous positions in the array is taken. The algorithm then traces back the path in the array to find the longest common subsequence. The time complexity of this algorithm is O(mn), where m and n are the lengths of the two input strings.

